{"title_page": "Augie Hoffmann", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image =  \n|number=<!--74-->  \n| current_team = Rutgers Scarlet Knights \n|position = Running Backs Coach <!--Guard-->  \n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1981|2|23}}\n|birth_place= [[Park Ridge, New Jersey]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=2\n|weight_lbs=315\n|high_school=[[Saint Joseph Regional High School|Saint Joseph Regional]] ([[Montvale, New Jersey]])\n|college=[[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]]\n|undraftedyear=2006\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2006}})*\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] (2014\u20132019)<br> Head Coach\n* [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]] (2020\u2013present)<br>Running Backs Coach \n|highlights=\n* Scanlan Award winner (2003)\n|nfl=2505803\n|pfr=\n}}\n\n'''August W. \"Augie\" Hoffmann III''' (February 23, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[guard (football)|guard]] and the current running backs coach at [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]. Hoffmann attended [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] in neighboring [[Montvale, New Jersey]].<ref>Dicker, Ron. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01E3DC1E38F937A35751C0A96F958260 \"COLLEGE FOOTBALL; Texas Makes the Passing Grade: Simms Signs Up\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 4, 1999. Accessed September 30, 2007. \"Boston College received commitments from several prominent New Jersey players, including running back William Green (6-1, 220) of Holy Spirit in Absecon and linemen Augie Hoffman (6-4, 315) of St. Joseph's in Montvale and Tom Martin (6-5, 245) of Howell.\"</ref> He then went to [[Boston College]], where he played football all four years.\n\nHe was signed by the [[New Orleans Saints]] to a Reserve/Future contract on January 3, 2006.\n\n==Coaching Career==\nIn July 2009 it was announced that he would return to [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|St. Joe's]], as an English teacher and head freshman football coach and assistant to the varsity.<ref>Czerwinski, Mark. [http://www.northjersey.com/hssports/Hoffman_St_Joseph_reunited.html \"Hoffman, St. Joseph Reunited\"]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, \"[[The Bergen Record]]\" July 6, 2009. \"Hoffman has been hired as an English teacher and head freshman football coach at St. Joseph. We always hear high school athletes talk about tradition and the impact life in the program makes on them, and Hoffman's return is living proof of just how indelible a mark that experience leaves.\"</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2013, it was announced that he would take over as head coach of the [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|St. Joe's]] Green Knights Varsity Football team.<ref>Czerwinski, Mark.[http://www.northjersey.com/sports/St_Joseph_football_coach_Tony_Karcich_steps_down_after_29_years.html \"St. Joseph's caring coach Tony Karcich exits triumphantly\"], \"[[NorthJersey.com]]\" December 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2020 it was announced that Augie would join the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] as a running backs coach and help lead the team to its former glory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scarletknights.com/sports/football/roster/coaches/augie-hoffmann/3004|title=Augie Hoffmann - Football Coach|website=Rutgers University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nfl.com/players/playerpage/501466 NFL player profile for Augie Hoffman]\n*[https://scarletknights.com/sports/football/roster/coaches/augie-hoffmann/3004 Rutgers football Augie Hoffman coaching profile]<br />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffmann, Augie}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football offensive guards]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:People from Park Ridge, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Saint Joseph Regional High School alumni]]\n{{offensive-lineman-1980s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image =  \n|number=<!--74-->  \n| current_team = Rutgers Scarlet Knights \n|position = Running Backs Coach <!--Guard-->  \n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1981|2|23}}\n|birth_place= [[Park Ridge, New Jersey]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=2\n|weight_lbs=315\n|high_school=[[Saint Joseph Regional High School|Saint Joseph Regional]] ([[Montvale, New Jersey]])\n|college=[[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]]\n|undraftedyear=2006\n|pastteams=\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2006}})*\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] (2014\u20132019)<br> Head Coach\n* [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]] (2020\u2013present)<br>Running Backs Coach \n|highlights=\n* Scanlan Award winner (2003)\n|nfl=2505803\n|pfr=\n}}\n\n'''August W. \"Augie\" Hoffmann III''' (February 23, 1981) is a former [[American football]] [[guard (football)|guard]] and the current running backs coach at Rutgers. Hoffmann attended [[Saint Joseph Regional High School]] in neighboring [[Montvale, New Jersey]].<ref>Dicker, Ron. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01E3DC1E38F937A35751C0A96F958260 \"COLLEGE FOOTBALL; Texas Makes the Passing Grade: Simms Signs Up\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 4, 1999. Accessed September 30, 2007. \"Boston College received commitments from several prominent New Jersey players, including running back William Green (6-1, 220) of Holy Spirit in Absecon and linemen Augie Hoffman (6-4, 315) of St. Joseph's in Montvale and Tom Martin (6-5, 245) of Howell.\"</ref> He then went to [[Boston College]], where he played football all four years.\n\nHe was signed by the [[New Orleans Saints]] to a Reserve/Future contract on January 3, 2006.\n\n==Coaching Career==\nIn July 2009 it was announced that he would return to [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|St. Joe's]], as an English teacher and head freshman football coach and assistant to the varsity.<ref>Czerwinski, Mark. [http://www.northjersey.com/hssports/Hoffman_St_Joseph_reunited.html \"Hoffman, St. Joseph Reunited\"]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, \"[[The Bergen Record]]\" July 6, 2009. \"Hoffman has been hired as an English teacher and head freshman football coach at St. Joseph. We always hear high school athletes talk about tradition and the impact life in the program makes on them, and Hoffman's return is living proof of just how indelible a mark that experience leaves.\"</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2013, it was announced that he would take over as head coach of the [[Saint Joseph Regional High School|St. Joe's]] Green Knights Varsity Football team.<ref>Czerwinski, Mark.[http://www.northjersey.com/sports/St_Joseph_football_coach_Tony_Karcich_steps_down_after_29_years.html \"St. Joseph's caring coach Tony Karcich exits triumphantly\"], \"[[NorthJersey.com]]\" December 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2020 it was announced that Augie would join the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] as a running backs coach and help lead the team to its former glory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scarletknights.com/sports/football/roster/coaches/augie-hoffmann/3004|title=Augie Hoffmann - Football Coach|website=Rutgers University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nfl.com/players/playerpage/501466 NFL player profile for Augie Hoffman]\n*[https://scarletknights.com/sports/football/roster/coaches/augie-hoffmann/3004 Rutgers football Augie Hoffman coaching profile]<br />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffmann, Augie}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football offensive guards]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:People from Park Ridge, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Saint Joseph Regional High School alumni]]\n{{offensive-lineman-1980s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bigmike2346", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augie_Hoffmann"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the environment", "text_new": "{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{short description|Impact of COVID-19 outbreak on environmental issues}}\n[[File:Pollutant Drops in wuhan china due to virus.png|thumb|Images from the [[NASA Earth Observatory]] show a stark drop in pollution in Wuhan, China, when comparing [[Nitrogen dioxide|NO<sub>2</sub>]] levels in early 2019 (top) and early 2020 (bottom).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china |title=Earth Observatory |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162640/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china |archive-date=2020-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe worldwide disruption caused by the  [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|<noinclude>2019\u201320 </noinclude>coronavirus pandemic]] has resulted in numerous impacts on the [[natural environment|environment]] and the [[climate]]. The severe [[Socio-economic_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic#Transportation|decline in planned travel]]<ref name=\"bbcOverview1\">{{cite web |last1=Team |first1=The Visual and Data Journalism |title=Coronavirus: A visual guide to the pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51235105 |website=[[BBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327231951/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51235105 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> has caused many regions to experience a drop in [[air pollution]]. In China, [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdowns]] and other measures resulted in a 25{{nbsp}}percent reduction in [[greenhouse gas|carbon emissions]],<ref name=\"DIm4R\">{{cite web |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |title=Analysis: Coronavirus has temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter |last=Myllyvirta |first=Lauri |work=CarbonBrief |date=19 February 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304082845/https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> which one [[Earth system science|Earth systems]] scientist estimated may have saved at least 77,000 lives over two months.<ref name=\"mcmahon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffmcmahon/2020/03/16/coronavirus-lockdown-may-have-saved-77000-lives-in-china-just-from-pollution-reduction/ |title=Study: Coronavirus Lockdown Likely Saved 77,000 Lives In China Just By Reducing Pollution |last=McMahon |first=Jeff |work=[[Forbes]] |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317041245/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffmcmahon/2020/03/16/coronavirus-lockdown-may-have-saved-77000-lives-in-china-just-from-pollution-reduction/ |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the outbreak has also disrupted [[Environmental policy|environmental diplomacy]] efforts, including causing the postponement of the [[2020 United Nations Climate Change Conference]],<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.climatechangenews.com/2020/04/01/cop26-climate-talks-postponed-2021-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=Cop26 climate talks postponed to 2021 amid coronavirus pandemic |date=1 April 2020 |website=Climate Home News |language=en |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404132430/https://www.climatechangenews.com/2020/04/01/cop26-climate-talks-postponed-2021-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/ |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Coronavirus recession|economic fallout]] from it is predicted to slow investment in [[green energy]] technologies.<ref name=\"9mMFi\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-could-weaken-climate-change-action-hit-clean-energy.html |title=Coronavirus could weaken climate change action and hit clean energy investment, researchers warn |author=Newburger, Emma |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315223847/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-could-weaken-climate-change-action-hit-clean-energy.html |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nUp to 2020, increases in the amount of [[Greenhouse gas|greenhouse gases]] produced since the beginning of the [[Industrialisation|industrialization]] epoch caused average global temperatures on the Earth to rise, causing effects including the melting of glaciers and [[Sea level rise|rising sea levels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/sealevel.html|title=Is sea level rising?|website=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172232/https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/sealevel.html|archive-date=2020-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/climate-change/|title=Climate Change|date=2019-03-28|website=[[National Geographic Society]]|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231070002/https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/climate-change/|archive-date=2019-12-31|url-status=live}}</ref> In various forms, human activity caused [[environmental degradation]], an [[Anthropogenic hazard|anthropogenic]] impact.\n\nPrior to the COVID-19 [[pandemic]], measures that were expected to be recommended to health authorities in the case of a [[pandemic]] included [[Quarantine|quarantines]] and [[social distancing]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Madhav|first=Nita|title=Pandemics: Risks, Impacts, and Mitigation|date=2017|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/|work=Disease Control Priorities: Improving Health and Reducing Poverty|editor-last=Jamison|editor-first=Dean T.|edition=3rd|publisher=The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|isbn=978-1-4648-0527-1|pmid=30212163|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Oppenheim|first2=Ben|last3=Gallivan|first3=Mark|last4=Mulembakani|first4=Prime|last5=Rubin|first5=Edward|last6=Wolfe|first6=Nathan|doi=10.1596/978-1-4648-0527-1/pt5.ch17|doi-broken-date=2020-04-13|editor2-last=Gelband|editor2-first=Hellen|editor3-last=Horton|editor3-first=Susan|editor4-last=Jha|editor4-first=Prabhat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323153254/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/|archive-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIndependently, also prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, researchers argued that reduced economic activity would help decrease global warming, air and marine pollution, allowing the environment to slowly flourish.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kopnina|first=Helen|last2=Washington|first2=Haydn|last3=Taylor|first3=Bron|last4=J Piccolo|first4=John|date=2018-02-01|title=Anthropocentrism: More than Just a Misunderstood Problem|journal=Journal of Agricultural and Environmental Ethics|language=en|volume=31|issue=1|pages=109\u2013127|doi=10.1007/s10806-018-9711-1|issn=1573-322X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Valent\u00ed|date=2016-09-01|title=The humanized Earth system (HES)|journal=The Holocene|language=en|volume=26|issue=9|pages=1513\u20131516|doi=10.1177/0959683616640053|bibcode=2016Holoc..26.1513R|issn=0959-6836}}</ref>\n\n==Air pollution==\n[[File:Nitrogen_dioxide_Density_Change_In_China_Due_To_Coronavirus.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nitrogen_dioxide_Density_Change_In_China_Due_To_Coronavirus.png|alt=|left|thumb|TROPOMI data shows the NO2 levels in China in the beginning of 2020. Image from [https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china Earth Observatory].]]\nDue to the coronavirus outbreak's impact [[Socio-economic_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic#Transportation|on travel]] and industry, many regions experienced a drop in [[air pollution]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watts |first1=Jonathan |last2=Kommenda |first2=Niko |date=23 March 2020 |title=Coronavirus pandemic leading to huge drop in air pollution |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404031855/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Reducing air pollution can reduce both [[climate change]] and COVID-19 risks<ref>{{Cite news|last=editor|first=Damian Carrington Environment|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/07/air-pollution-linked-to-far-higher-covid-19-death-rates-study-finds|title=Air pollution linked to far higher Covid-19 death rates, study finds|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409033624/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/07/air-pollution-linked-to-far-higher-covid-19-death-rates-study-finds|archive-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live}}</ref> but it is not yet clear which types of air pollution (if any) are common risks to both climate change and COVID-19. The [[Centre for Research on Energy and Clean Air]] reported that methods to contain the spread of coronavirus, such as quarantines and [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel bans]], resulted in a 25{{nbsp}}percent reduction of [[greenhouse gas|carbon emission]] in China.<ref name=\"DIm4R\" /><ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> In the first month of [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdowns]], China produced approximately 200&nbsp;million fewer metric tons of [[carbon dioxide]] than the same period in 2019, due to the reduction in air traffic, oil refining, and coal consumption.<ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> One [[Earth system science|Earth systems]] scientist estimated that this reduction may have saved at least 77,000 lives.<ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> However, Sarah Ladislaw from the [[Center for Strategic & International Studies]] argued that reductions in emissions due to economic downturns should not be seen as beneficial, stating that China's attempts to return to previous rates of growth amidst trade wars and supply chain disruptions in the energy market will worsen its environmental impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/global-impacts-coronavirus-outbreak |title=The Global Impacts of the Coronavirus Outbreak |website=www.csis.org |language=en |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407202137/https://www.csis.org/analysis/global-impacts-coronavirus-outbreak |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between 1&nbsp;January and 11 March 2020, the [[European Space Agency]] observed a marked decline in [[nitrous oxide]] emissions from cars, power plants, and factories in the [[Po Valley]] region in northern Italy, coinciding with lockdowns in the region.<ref name=\"StEML\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-italy-pollution/air-pollution-clears-in-northern-italy-after-coronavirus-lockdown-satellite-shows-idUSKBN2102X4 |title=Air pollution clears in northern Italy after coronavirus lockdown, satellite shows |last=Green |first=Matthew |agency=Reuters |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316105932/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-italy-pollution/air-pollution-clears-in-northern-italy-after-coronavirus-lockdown-satellite-shows-idUSKBN2102X4 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In Venice, the water in the canals cleared and experienced an increased presence of fish and waterfowl; the Venice mayor's office clarified that the increase in water clarity was due to the settling of sediment that is disturbed by boat traffic and mentioned the decrease in air pollution along the waterways.<ref name=\"63GlJ\">{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Empty motorway due to 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic (A1 motorway, Slovenia).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|The reduction in motor vehicle traffic has led to a drop in air pollution levels. Inset is the empty [[A1 motorway (Slovenia)|A1 motorway]] in Slovenia on 22 March 2020]]\n[[NASA]] and [[European Space Agency|ESA]] have been monitoring how the Nitrogen dioxide gases dropped significantly during the initial Chinese phase of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] pandemic. The economic slowdown from the virus drastically dropped pollution levels, especially in cities like Wuhan, China by 25%.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china|title=Airborne Nitrogen Dioxide Plummets Over China|date=2020-02-28|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162640/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china|archive-date=2020-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter|title=Analysis: Coronavirus temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter|date=2020-02-19|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304082845/https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter|archive-date=2020-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> NASA uses a [[ozone monitoring instrument]] (OMI) to analyze and observe the [[ozone layer]] and pollutants such as NO2, aerosols and others. This instrument helped NASA to process and interpret the data coming in due to the lock-downs worldwide<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aura.gsfc.nasa.gov/omi.html|title=NASA Aura OMI|last=|first=|date=|website=NASA Aura|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303075331/https://aura.gsfc.nasa.gov/omi.html|archive-date=2020-03-03|access-date=}}</ref>. According to NASA scientists, the drop in NO2 pollution began in Wuhan, China and slowly spread to the rest of the world. The drop was also very drastic because the virus coincided with the same time of year as the [[Lunar calendar|lunar year]] celebrations in China. For this festival, factories and businesses close for the last week of January to celebrate the lunar year festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chinesenewyear.net/|website=chinesenewyear.net|access-date=2020-04-06|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229110431/https://chinesenewyear.net/|archive-date=2020-02-29|url-status=live}}</ref> The drop in NO<sub>2</sub> in China did not achieve an air quality of the standard considered acceptable by health authorities. Other pollutants in the air such as [[aerosol]] emissions remained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/blogs/earthmatters/2020/03/05/how-the-coronavirus-is-and-is-not-affecting-the-environment/|title=Earth Matters - How the Coronavirus Is (and Is Not) Affecting the Environment|date=2020-03-05|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406235222/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/blogs/earthmatters/2020/03/05/how-the-coronavirus-is-and-is-not-affecting-the-environment/|archive-date=2020-04-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Research and development==\nDespite a temporary decline in global carbon emissions, the [[International Energy Agency]] warned that the economic turmoil caused by the coronavirus outbreak may prevent or delay companies from investing in [[sustainable energy|green energy]].<ref name=\"9mMFi\"/><ref name=\"pH2jp\">{{cite web |url=https://text.npr.org/s.php?sId=820268157 |title=Text-Only NPR.org : Climate Change Push Fuels Split On Coronavirus Stimulus |publisher=NPR |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404050115/https://text.npr.org/s.php?sId=820268157 |archive-date=2020-04-04 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"dEHl9\">{{cite web |url=https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis |title=Put clean energy at the heart of stimulus plans to counter the coronavirus crisis\u2014Analysis |website=IEA |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402134500/https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis |archive-date=2020-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, extended quarantine periods have boosted adoption of remote work policies.<ref name=\"C3vSo\">{{Cite news |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/10/coronavirus-remote-flexible-work-from-home/ |title=Commentary: Coronavirus may finally force businesses to adopt workplaces of the future |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405200635/https://fortune.com/2020/03/10/coronavirus-remote-flexible-work-from-home/ |archive-date=2020-04-05 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Foevb\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/business/coronavirus-businesses.html |title=1,000 Workers, Go Home: Companies Act to Ward Off Coronavirus |first=David |last=Yaffe-Bellany |date=26 February 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304092105/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/business/coronavirus-businesses.html |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a consequence of the unprecedented use of disposable face masks, significant numbers are entering the natural environment, adding to the worldwide burden of plastic waste.<ref name=\"jRX9D\">{{cite news |title=Discarded coronavirus masks clutter Hong Kong's beaches, trails |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-hongkong-environme/discarded-coronavirus-masks-clutter-hong-kongs-beaches-trails-idUSKBN20Z0PP |agency=Reuters |publisher=Hong Kong (Reuters) |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321024008/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-hongkong-environme/discarded-coronavirus-masks-clutter-hong-kongs-beaches-trails-idUSKBN20Z0PP |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts]] (ECMWF) announced that a worldwide reduction in aircraft flights due to the pandemic could impact the accuracy of weather forecasts, citing commercial airlines' use of [[Aircraft Meteorological Data Relay]] (AMDAR) as an integral contribution to weather forecast accuracy. The ECMWF predicted that AMDAR coverage would decrease by 65% or more due to the drop in commercial flights.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecmwf.int/en/about/media-centre/news/2020/drop-aircraft-observations-could-have-impact-weather-forecasts |title=Drop in aircraft observations could have impact on weather forecasts |author=Press release |work=European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326005351/https://www.ecmwf.int/en/about/media-centre/news/2020/drop-aircraft-observations-could-have-impact-weather-forecasts |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nThe pandemic has also impacted [[Environmental policy|environmental diplomacy]] and [[Climate policy|climate diplomacy]], as the [[2020 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] was postponed to 2021 in response to the pandemic after its venue was converted to a field hospital. This conference was crucial as nations were scheduled to submit enhanced [[Intended nationally determined contributions|nationally determined contributions]] to the [[Paris Agreement]], with enhanced ambition. The pandemic also limits the ability of nations, particularly developing nations with low state capacity, to submit nationally determined contributions, as they focus on the pandemic.<ref name=\"UN\"/>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' argued for three possible risks: that preparations for the November 2020 Glasgow conference planned to follow the 2015 [[Paris Agreement]] were disrupted; that the public would see global warming as a lower priority issue than the pandemic, weakening the pressure on politicians; and that a desire to \"restart\" the global economy would cause an excess in extra greenhouse gas production. However the drop in oil prices during the [[coronavirus recession]] could be a good opportunity to get rid of [[fossil fuel]] subsidies, according to the Executive Director of the International Energy Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Put clean energy at the heart of stimulus plans to counter the coronavirus crisis \u2013 Analysis|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402134500/https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis|archive-date=2020-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Carbon Tracker]] argues that China should not stimulate the economy by building planned [[Coal-fired power station|coal-fired power stations]], because many would have negative [[Cash flow|cashflow]] and would become [[stranded assets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/reports/political-decisions-economic-realities/|title=Political decisions, economic realities: The underlying operating cashflows of coal power during COVID-19|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Predicted rebound effect ==\nThe \"restarting\" of greenhouse-gas producing industries and transport following the COVID-19 lockdowns was hypothesised as an event that would contribute to increasing greenhouse gas production rather than reducing it. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/story/six-nature-facts-related-coronaviruses United Nations: Six Nature Facts Related to Coronaviruses]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Environment]]\n[[Category:2019 in the environment|Coronavirus pandemic impact]]\n[[Category:2020 in the environment|Coronavirus pandemic impact]]\n[[Category:Environment and health]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{short description|Impact of COVID-19 outbreak on environmental issues}}\n[[File:Pollutant Drops in wuhan china due to virus.png|thumb|Images from the [[NASA Earth Observatory]] show a stark drop in pollution in Wuhan, China, when comparing [[Nitrogen dioxide|NO<sub>2</sub>]] levels in early 2019 (top) and early 2020 (bottom).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china |title=Earth Observatory |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162640/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china |archive-date=2020-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe worldwide disruption caused by the  [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|<noinclude>2019\u201320 </noinclude>coronavirus pandemic]] has resulted in numerous impacts on the [[natural environment|environment]] and the [[climate]]. The severe [[Socio-economic_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic#Transportation|decline in planned travel]]<ref name=\"bbcOverview1\">{{cite web |last1=Team |first1=The Visual and Data Journalism |title=Coronavirus: A visual guide to the pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51235105 |website=[[BBC News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327231951/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-51235105 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=28 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> has caused many regions to experience a drop in [[air pollution]]. In China, [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdowns]] and other measures resulted in a 25{{nbsp}}percent reduction in [[greenhouse gas|carbon emissions]],<ref name=\"DIm4R\">{{cite web |url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |title=Analysis: Coronavirus has temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter |last=Myllyvirta |first=Lauri |work=CarbonBrief |date=19 February 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304082845/https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> which one [[Earth system science|Earth systems]] scientist estimated may have saved at least 77,000 lives over two months.<ref name=\"mcmahon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffmcmahon/2020/03/16/coronavirus-lockdown-may-have-saved-77000-lives-in-china-just-from-pollution-reduction/ |title=Study: Coronavirus Lockdown Likely Saved 77,000 Lives In China Just By Reducing Pollution |last=McMahon |first=Jeff |work=[[Forbes]] |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317041245/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffmcmahon/2020/03/16/coronavirus-lockdown-may-have-saved-77000-lives-in-china-just-from-pollution-reduction/ |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the outbreak has also disrupted [[Environmental policy|environmental diplomacy]] efforts, including causing the postponement of the [[2020 United Nations Climate Change Conference]],<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.climatechangenews.com/2020/04/01/cop26-climate-talks-postponed-2021-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/ |title=Cop26 climate talks postponed to 2021 amid coronavirus pandemic |date=1 April 2020 |website=Climate Home News |language=en |access-date=2 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404132430/https://www.climatechangenews.com/2020/04/01/cop26-climate-talks-postponed-2021-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/ |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Coronavirus recession|economic fallout]] from it is predicted to slow investment in [[green energy]] technologies.<ref name=\"9mMFi\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-could-weaken-climate-change-action-hit-clean-energy.html |title=Coronavirus could weaken climate change action and hit clean energy investment, researchers warn |author=Newburger, Emma |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315223847/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-could-weaken-climate-change-action-hit-clean-energy.html |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nUp to 2020, increases in the amount of [[Greenhouse gas|greenhouse gases]] produced since the beginning of the industrialisation epoch caused average global temperatures on the Earth to rise, causing effects including the melting of glaciers and [[Sea level rise|rising sea levels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/sealevel.html|title=Is sea level rising?|website=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172232/https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/sealevel.html|archive-date=2020-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/climate-change/|title=Climate Change|date=2019-03-28|website=[[National Geographic Society]]|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231070002/https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/climate-change/|archive-date=2019-12-31|url-status=live}}</ref> In various forms, human activity caused environmental degradation, an [[Anthropogenic hazard|anthropogenic]] impact.\n\nPrior to the COVID-19 [[pandemic]], measures that were expected to be recommended to health authorities in the case of a [[pandemic]] included [[Quarantine|quarantines]] and [[social distancing]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Madhav|first=Nita|title=Pandemics: Risks, Impacts, and Mitigation|date=2017|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/|work=Disease Control Priorities: Improving Health and Reducing Poverty|editor-last=Jamison|editor-first=Dean T.|edition=3rd|publisher=The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development / The World Bank|isbn=978-1-4648-0527-1|pmid=30212163|access-date=2020-04-06|last2=Oppenheim|first2=Ben|last3=Gallivan|first3=Mark|last4=Mulembakani|first4=Prime|last5=Rubin|first5=Edward|last6=Wolfe|first6=Nathan|doi=10.1596/978-1-4648-0527-1/pt5.ch17|doi-broken-date=2020-04-13|editor2-last=Gelband|editor2-first=Hellen|editor3-last=Horton|editor3-first=Susan|editor4-last=Jha|editor4-first=Prabhat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323153254/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/|archive-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIndependently, also prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, researchers argued that reduced economic activity would help decrease global warming, air and marine pollution, allowing the environment to slowly flourish.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kopnina|first=Helen|last2=Washington|first2=Haydn|last3=Taylor|first3=Bron|last4=J Piccolo|first4=John|date=2018-02-01|title=Anthropocentrism: More than Just a Misunderstood Problem|journal=Journal of Agricultural and Environmental Ethics|language=en|volume=31|issue=1|pages=109\u2013127|doi=10.1007/s10806-018-9711-1|issn=1573-322X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Valent\u00ed|date=2016-09-01|title=The humanized Earth system (HES)|journal=The Holocene|language=en|volume=26|issue=9|pages=1513\u20131516|doi=10.1177/0959683616640053|bibcode=2016Holoc..26.1513R|issn=0959-6836}}</ref>\n\n==Air pollution==\n[[File:Nitrogen_dioxide_Density_Change_In_China_Due_To_Coronavirus.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nitrogen_dioxide_Density_Change_In_China_Due_To_Coronavirus.png|alt=|left|thumb|TROPOMI data shows the NO2 levels in China in the beginning of 2020. Image from [https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china Earth Observatory].]]\nDue to the coronavirus outbreak's impact [[Socio-economic_impact_of_the_2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic#Transportation|on travel]] and industry, many regions experienced a drop in [[air pollution]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watts |first1=Jonathan |last2=Kommenda |first2=Niko |date=23 March 2020 |title=Coronavirus pandemic leading to huge drop in air pollution |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404031855/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/23/coronavirus-pandemic-leading-to-huge-drop-in-air-pollution |archive-date=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Reducing air pollution can reduce both climate change and COVID-19 risks<ref>{{Cite news|last=editor|first=Damian Carrington Environment|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/07/air-pollution-linked-to-far-higher-covid-19-death-rates-study-finds|title=Air pollution linked to far higher Covid-19 death rates, study finds|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409033624/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/apr/07/air-pollution-linked-to-far-higher-covid-19-death-rates-study-finds|archive-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live}}</ref> but it is not yet clear which types of air pollution (if any) are common risks to both climate change and COVID-19. The [[Centre for Research on Energy and Clean Air]] reported that methods to contain the spread of coronavirus, such as quarantines and [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel bans]], resulted in a 25{{nbsp}}percent reduction of [[greenhouse gas|carbon emission]] in China.<ref name=\"DIm4R\" /><ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> In the first month of [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdowns]], China produced approximately 200&nbsp;million fewer metric tons of [[carbon dioxide]] than the same period in 2019, due to the reduction in air traffic, oil refining, and coal consumption.<ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> One [[Earth system science|Earth systems]] scientist estimated that this reduction may have saved at least 77,000 lives.<ref name=\"mcmahon\" /> However, Sarah Ladislaw from the [[Center for Strategic & International Studies]] argued that reductions in emissions due to economic downturns should not be seen as beneficial, stating that China's attempts to return to previous rates of growth amidst trade wars and supply chain disruptions in the energy market will worsen its environmental impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/global-impacts-coronavirus-outbreak |title=The Global Impacts of the Coronavirus Outbreak |website=www.csis.org |language=en |access-date=4 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407202137/https://www.csis.org/analysis/global-impacts-coronavirus-outbreak |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between 1&nbsp;January and 11 March 2020, the [[European Space Agency]] observed a marked decline in [[nitrous oxide]] emissions from cars, power plants, and factories in the [[Po Valley]] region in northern Italy, coinciding with lockdowns in the region.<ref name=\"StEML\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-italy-pollution/air-pollution-clears-in-northern-italy-after-coronavirus-lockdown-satellite-shows-idUSKBN2102X4 |title=Air pollution clears in northern Italy after coronavirus lockdown, satellite shows |last=Green |first=Matthew |agency=Reuters |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316105932/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-italy-pollution/air-pollution-clears-in-northern-italy-after-coronavirus-lockdown-satellite-shows-idUSKBN2102X4 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In Venice, the water in the canals cleared and experienced an increased presence of fish and waterfowl; the Venice mayor's office clarified that the increase in water clarity was due to the settling of sediment that is disturbed by boat traffic and mentioned the decrease in air pollution along the waterways.<ref name=\"63GlJ\">{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |title=As Italy quarantines over coronavirus, swans appear in Venice canals, dolphins swim up playfully |author=Srikanth, Anagha |work=The Hill |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215915/https://thehill.com/changing-america/sustainability/environment/488286-italys-coronavirus-lockdown-shows-what-nature |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Empty motorway due to 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic (A1 motorway, Slovenia).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|The reduction in motor vehicle traffic has led to a drop in air pollution levels. Inset is the empty [[A1 motorway (Slovenia)|A1 motorway]] in Slovenia on 22 March 2020]]\n[[NASA]] and [[European Space Agency|ESA]] have been monitoring how the Nitrogen dioxide gases dropped significantly during the initial Chinese phase of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] pandemic. The economic slowdown from the virus drastically dropped pollution levels, especially in cities like Wuhan, China by 25%.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china|title=Airborne Nitrogen Dioxide Plummets Over China|date=2020-02-28|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162640/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/images/146362/airborne-nitrogen-dioxide-plummets-over-china|archive-date=2020-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter|title=Analysis: Coronavirus temporarily reduced China's CO2 emissions by a quarter|date=2020-02-19|website=Carbon Brief|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304082845/https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter|archive-date=2020-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> NASA uses a [[ozone monitoring instrument]] (OMI) to analyze and observe the [[ozone layer]] and pollutants such as NO2, aerosols and others. This instrument helped NASA to process and interpret the data coming in due to the lock-downs worldwide<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aura.gsfc.nasa.gov/omi.html|title=NASA Aura OMI|last=|first=|date=|website=NASA Aura|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303075331/https://aura.gsfc.nasa.gov/omi.html|archive-date=2020-03-03|access-date=}}</ref>. According to NASA scientists, the drop in NO2 pollution began in Wuhan, China and slowly spread to the rest of the world. The drop was also very drastic because the virus coincided with the same time of year as the [[Lunar calendar|lunar year]] celebrations in China. For this festival, factories and businesses close for the last week of January to celebrate the lunar year festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chinesenewyear.net/|website=chinesenewyear.net|access-date=2020-04-06|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229110431/https://chinesenewyear.net/|archive-date=2020-02-29|url-status=live}}</ref> The drop in NO<sub>2</sub> in China did not achieve an air quality of the standard considered acceptable by health authorities. Other pollutants in the air such as [[aerosol]] emissions remained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/blogs/earthmatters/2020/03/05/how-the-coronavirus-is-and-is-not-affecting-the-environment/|title=Earth Matters - How the Coronavirus Is (and Is Not) Affecting the Environment|date=2020-03-05|website=earthobservatory.nasa.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406235222/https://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/blogs/earthmatters/2020/03/05/how-the-coronavirus-is-and-is-not-affecting-the-environment/|archive-date=2020-04-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Research and development==\nDespite a temporary decline in global carbon emissions, the [[International Energy Agency]] warned that the economic turmoil caused by the coronavirus outbreak may prevent or delay companies from investing in [[sustainable energy|green energy]].<ref name=\"9mMFi\"/><ref name=\"pH2jp\">{{cite web |url=https://text.npr.org/s.php?sId=820268157 |title=Text-Only NPR.org : Climate Change Push Fuels Split On Coronavirus Stimulus |publisher=NPR |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404050115/https://text.npr.org/s.php?sId=820268157 |archive-date=2020-04-04 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"dEHl9\">{{cite web |url=https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis |title=Put clean energy at the heart of stimulus plans to counter the coronavirus crisis\u2014Analysis |website=IEA |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402134500/https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis |archive-date=2020-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, extended quarantine periods have boosted adoption of remote work policies.<ref name=\"C3vSo\">{{Cite news |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/10/coronavirus-remote-flexible-work-from-home/ |title=Commentary: Coronavirus may finally force businesses to adopt workplaces of the future |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |access-date=2020-04-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405200635/https://fortune.com/2020/03/10/coronavirus-remote-flexible-work-from-home/ |archive-date=2020-04-05 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Foevb\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/business/coronavirus-businesses.html |title=1,000 Workers, Go Home: Companies Act to Ward Off Coronavirus |first=David |last=Yaffe-Bellany |date=26 February 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304092105/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/business/coronavirus-businesses.html |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a consequence of the unprecedented use of disposable face masks, significant numbers are entering the natural environment, adding to the worldwide burden of plastic waste.<ref name=\"jRX9D\">{{cite news |title=Discarded coronavirus masks clutter Hong Kong's beaches, trails |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-hongkong-environme/discarded-coronavirus-masks-clutter-hong-kongs-beaches-trails-idUSKBN20Z0PP |agency=Reuters |publisher=Hong Kong (Reuters) |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321024008/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-hongkong-environme/discarded-coronavirus-masks-clutter-hong-kongs-beaches-trails-idUSKBN20Z0PP |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts]] (ECMWF) announced that a worldwide reduction in aircraft flights due to the pandemic could impact the accuracy of weather forecasts, citing commercial airlines' use of [[Aircraft Meteorological Data Relay]] (AMDAR) as an integral contribution to weather forecast accuracy. The ECMWF predicted that AMDAR coverage would decrease by 65% or more due to the drop in commercial flights.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ecmwf.int/en/about/media-centre/news/2020/drop-aircraft-observations-could-have-impact-weather-forecasts |title=Drop in aircraft observations could have impact on weather forecasts |author=Press release |work=European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326005351/https://www.ecmwf.int/en/about/media-centre/news/2020/drop-aircraft-observations-could-have-impact-weather-forecasts |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nThe pandemic has also impacted [[Environmental policy|environmental diplomacy]] and [[Climate policy|climate diplomacy]], as the [[2020 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] was postponed to 2021 in response to the pandemic after its venue was converted to a field hospital. This conference was crucial as nations were scheduled to submit enhanced [[Intended nationally determined contributions|nationally determined contributions]] to the [[Paris Agreement]], with enhanced ambition. The pandemic also limits the ability of nations, particularly developing nations with low state capacity, to submit nationally determined contributions, as they focus on the pandemic.<ref name=\"UN\"/>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' argued for three possible risks: that preparations for the November 2020 Glasgow conference planned to follow the 2015 [[Paris Agreement]] were disrupted; that the public would see global warming as a lower priority issue than the pandemic, weakening the pressure on politicians; and that a desire to \"restart\" the global economy would cause an excess in extra greenhouse gas production. However the drop in oil prices during the [[coronavirus recession]] could be a good opportunity to get rid of [[fossil fuel]] subsidies, according to the Executive Director of the International Energy Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Put clean energy at the heart of stimulus plans to counter the coronavirus crisis \u2013 Analysis|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402134500/https://www.iea.org/commentaries/put-clean-energy-at-the-heart-of-stimulus-plans-to-counter-the-coronavirus-crisis|archive-date=2020-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Carbon Tracker]] argues that China should not stimulate the economy by building planned [[Coal-fired power station|coal-fired power stations]], because many would have negative [[Cash flow|cashflow]] and would become [[stranded assets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/reports/political-decisions-economic-realities/|title=Political decisions, economic realities: The underlying operating cashflows of coal power during COVID-19|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Predicted rebound effect ==\nThe \"restarting\" of greenhouse-gas producing industries and transport following the COVID-19 lockdowns was hypothesised as an event that would contribute to increasing greenhouse gas production rather than reducing it. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/story/six-nature-facts-related-coronaviruses United Nations: Six Nature Facts Related to Coronaviruses]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Environment]]\n[[Category:2019 in the environment|Coronavirus pandemic impact]]\n[[Category:2020 in the environment|Coronavirus pandemic impact]]\n[[Category:Environment and health]]\n", "name_user": "Alvarezyusi", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_the_environment"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree shooting]] [[mass shooting]], [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' took place between April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] when Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CTV4\" /> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the morning of April 19 and ended when Wortman was shot dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia didn't use its emergency alert system to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 18 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Residents described Wortman as a polite man who often spent his time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with [[alcoholism]], and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Police Seek Motive for Canada Killing Spree by Amiable Denture Fitter, as Dumbstruck Families Mourn|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reeaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\" /> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree shooting]], [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' took place between April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] when Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CTV4\" /> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the morning of April 19 and ended when Wortman was shot dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia didn't use its emergency alert system to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 18 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Residents described Wortman as a polite man who often spent his time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with [[alcoholism]], and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Police Seek Motive for Canada Killing Spree by Amiable Denture Fitter, as Dumbstruck Families Mourn|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reeaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\" /> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Paleontologist99", "label": "safe", "comment": "see main page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
